Preheat the oven to 400 degrees. Bring a large #pot{} of water with a large pinch of @salt{} to a boil. Zest and halve the @lemon{1}. Slice one half into rounds for garnish, if desired. Mince or grate the @garlic{2%cloves}.

Add the @broccoli florets{6%ounce} to the boiling water and cook for ~{4-5%minutes}, until tender. Remove with a #slotted spoon{} and set aside.

> To preserve its bright green color, place the broccoli in a bowl of ice water after cooking.

Add the @linguine{6%ounce} to the boiling water you cooked the broccoli in and cook for ~{8-10%minutes}, until al dente. Drain, reserving ¼ cup pasta water.

Toss the @grape tomatoes{4%ounce} on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @olive oil{}, @salt{}, and @ground black pepper{}. Place in the oven for ~{10-12%minutes}, until they burst.

While the tomatoes roast, heat a drizzle of @olive oil{} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Pat the @skin-on salmon{12%ounce} dry with #paper towels{} and season on all sides with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}. Add the salmon to the pan and cook for ~{3-4%minutes} per side, until just opaque in the middle. Set aside, then remove and discard the salmon skin (if desired.)

In the same pan, heat @butter{2%tablespoon}, the garlic, and @chili flakes{1/4%teaspoon} over medium heat. Cook for ~{30%seconds}, until fragrant. Toss the drained pasta, lemon zest, @parmesan cheese{1%ounce}, broccoli, burst tomatoes, and ¼ cup pasta water into the pan and toss to combine. Cook, tossing, for ~{1-2%minutes}, until the sauce thickens. Season generously with @salt{} and freshly cracked @ground black pepper{}.

Serve the pasta with the salmon on top and finish with a squeeze of @lemon{}. Garnish with a lemon round, if desired, and enjoy!